#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:32(title)
msgid "Make Windows partitions available from Ubuntu"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:33(para)
msgid ""
"Windows partitions should be automatically available from any Ubuntu system. "
"If they are not, you can make them available using the <application>Disks "
"Manager</application>."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:36(para) C/partitionsandbooting.xml:174(para)
msgid "Open &disks;."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:39(para)
msgid ""
"Select the correct hard disk, and click <guilabel>Partitions</guilabel>."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:42(para)
msgid "Select the relevant partition, and click <guilabel>Enable</guilabel>."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:45(para)
msgid "To unmount the partition, click <guilabel>Disable</guilabel>."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:50(title)
msgid "Make Windows partitions automatically available"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:51(para)
msgid ""
"Windows partitions should be automatically available from Ubuntu. If they "
"are not, the following procedure will make them automatically available:"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:54(para)
msgid "Read <xref linkend=\"listpartitiontables\"/>"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:58(para)
msgid ""
"First make a directory where the partition can be made available "
"(\"mounted\"):"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:59(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo mkdir /media/windows\n"
"\t\t\t\t\t\t\t"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:64(para)
msgid ""
"Next, back up your disk configuration file and open the file in a text "
"editor with administrative privileges:"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:66(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\n"
"sudo cp /etc/fstab /etc/fstab_backup\n"
"sudo gedit /etc/fstab\n"
"\t\t\t\t\t\t"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:73(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "/dev/hda1 /media/windows ntfs umask=0222 0 0"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:72(para)
msgid "Append the following line at the end of file: <placeholder-1/>"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:76(para)
msgid ""
"Replace <emphasis role=\"bold\">/dev/hda1</emphasis> with the correct device "
"name for your partition."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:77(para)
msgid ""
"If your Windows partition uses the FAT32 filesystem, replace <emphasis "
"role=\"bold\">ntfs</emphasis> with <emphasis role=\"bold\">vfat</emphasis> "
"in the above command."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:78(para)
msgid ""
"If you have a FAT32 filesystem, it is also safe to allow read-write access. "
"To do this, change the value of <emphasis role=\"bold\">umask</emphasis> to "
"0000."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:82(para)
msgid ""
"Save the edited file (<ulink url=\"sample/fstab_automountntfs\">an "
"example</ulink>)."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:86(para)
msgid "The changes will take effect when the computer is restarted."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:91(title)
msgid "Run a system command automatically at startup"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:92(para)
msgid ""
"Sometimes it can be useful to run a custom command whenever your computer "
"starts up. To do this:"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:95(para)
msgid ""
"Edit the <application>crontab</application> with administrative privileges "
"(see <xref linkend=\"root-and-sudo\"/>):"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:96(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid "sudo crontab -e"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:99(para)
msgid "Insert the following line:"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:100(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid "@reboot /home/user/command"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:102(para)
msgid ""
"Replace <filename>/home/user/command</filename> with the full address to "
"your command."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:106(para)
msgid "Save the file and exit."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:111(title)
msgid "Change default operating system at boot"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:112(para)
msgid ""
"To change which operating system starts by default when the computer starts "
"up, edit the <application>grub</application> configuration file."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:115(para)
msgid ""
"Make a backup of the configuration file, and open it in a text editor:"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:116(screen)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"sudo cp /boot/grub/menu.lst /boot/grub/menu.lst_backup\n"
"sudo gedit /boot/grub/menu.lst"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:120(para)
msgid "Find this line:"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:121(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"...\n"
"default 0\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:126(para)
msgid "Replace with the following line:"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:127(programlisting)
#, no-wrap
msgid "default X"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:128(para)
msgid ""
"You should replace X with a number, according to the order which your "
"operating systems appear in the configuration file. You should start "
"counting from 0. For example, if you wish the default operating system to be "
"the first in the list, replace X with 0, if you wish the default operating "
"system to be the second in the list, replace X with 1, and so on."
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:131(para)
msgid ""
"Save the edited file (<ulink url=\"sample/menu.list_changedefaultosgrub\">an "
"example</ulink>)"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:139(title)
msgid "Configure startup services"
msgstr ""

#: C/partitionsandbooting.xml:140(para)
msgid ""
"This requires administrative privileges (see <xref linkend=\"root-and-"
"sudo\"/>)."
